ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Contagious ecthyma (orf) is an infectious dermatitis of sheep and goats,
affecting primarily the lips of young animals. It is more severe in goats
than sheep. Humans can be affected and the disease has been reported in
dogs that have eaten infected carcasses. The causal poxvirus is related to
those of pseudocowpox and bovine papular stomatitis. Infection occurs by
contact. The lesions, although characteristic, must be differentiated from
ulcerative dermatosis, which produces tissue destruction and crateriform
ulcers. Ecthyma usually affects younger animals than does ulcerative
dermatosis, although this is not always the case. The virus is highly
resistant to desiccation, having been recovered from dried crusts after 12
years. - Mod.TG
